pull_request.title: Kernel: Make console refreshes work again & allocate local socket descriptors more efficiently
pull_request.body:
The `add_timer_without_id()` approach introduced in c1635e7 doesn't actually work, because that function expects the deadline to be an actual timestamp rather than an interval. If it's given a timestamp that's in the past (as happened here), it'll just return without adding the timer to the queue. Further, fixing that wouldn't have made this setup work either, because it's not possible to schedule a timer while it's still active (which was the case here because the timer was being rescheduled from within itself).

To still get the benefits that that commit was trying to get, we now use a separate thread rather than a timer (and this approach actually works).

I've also included an optimization for `sys$recvmsg`, which makes WindowServer disappear from the kmalloc stack dumps when it's idle (though there's a bunch of other stuff, mainly to do with SysFS, that still makes the system quite slow when running with those enabled).

pull_request.body:
## üèóÔ∏è Terraform Baseline Infrastructure Implementation

This PR implements Issue #98 - Terraform baseline infrastructure for fresh environment creation.

### üìã What's Included

**Infrastructure Components:**
- ‚úÖ **Network Module**: Azure VNet with application and database subnets, NSGs, private DNS zones
- ‚úÖ **Database Module**: PostgreSQL Flexible Server with HA options and private endpoint support
- ‚úÖ **Storage Module**: Azure Blob Storage with lifecycle management and security features
- ‚úÖ **Monitoring Module**: Application Insights, Log Analytics with comprehensive alerting

**Environment Configurations:**
- ‚úÖ **Development**: Cost-optimized with basic tiers (B_Standard_B1ms, LRS storage)
- ‚úÖ **Production**: Enterprise-grade with HA, geo-redundancy, and enhanced security

**DevOps Automation:**
- ‚úÖ **Deployment Script** (`deploy.sh`): Automated infrastructure deployment
- ‚úÖ **Validation Script** (`validate.sh`): Pre-deployment checks and validation
- ‚úÖ **GitHub Actions Workflow**: CI/CD pipeline for infrastructure as code
- ‚úÖ **Comprehensive Documentation**: README with setup and usage instructions

### üéØ Key Features

**Security & Compliance:**
- Private endpoints for database and storage (production)
- Network security groups with least-privilege rules
- Encryption at rest and in transit
- Firewall rules and access controls

**High Availability & Backup:**
- PostgreSQL zone-redundant HA (production)
- Geo-redundant storage replication (production)
- Automated backup policies with configurable retention
- Point-in-time recovery capabilities

**Cost Optimization:**
- Environment-specific resource sizing
- Storage lifecycle management policies
- Development-optimized configurations
- Comprehensive resource tagging

### üìÅ Directory Structure

```
terraform/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ main.tf                     # Root Terraform configuration
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ variables.tf                # Variable definitions with validation
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ outputs.tf                  # Output values for CI/CD integration
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ deploy.sh                   # Deployment automation script
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ validate.sh                 # Pre-deployment validation
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ terraform.tfvars.example    # Configuration template
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ README.md                   # Comprehensive documentation
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ modules/                    # Reusable Terraform modules
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ network/               # VNet, subnets, NSGs, DNS
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ database/              # PostgreSQL Flexible Server
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ storage/               # Azure Blob Storage

‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ environments/              # Environment-specific configurations

‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ prod/terraform.tfvars  # Production environment settings
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ .github/workflows/terraform.yml  # CI/CD pipeline
```

### üöÄ Deployment Instructions

1. **Set Required Environment Variables:**
   ```bash
   export TF_VAR_alert_email_recipients='{"team":"alerts@company.com"}'
   ```

2. **Deploy Development Environment:**
   ```bash
   cd terraform
   ./validate.sh                    # Validate configuration
   ./deploy.sh -e dev -a plan      # Review planned changes
   ./deploy.sh -e dev -a apply     # Deploy infrastructure
   ```

3. **Deploy Production Environment:**
   ```bash
   ./deploy.sh -e prod -a plan     # Review production changes
   ./deploy.sh -e prod -a apply    # Deploy after approval
   ```

### üîß GitHub Secrets Required

Before using the CI/CD pipeline, configure these repository secrets:
- `AZURE_CREDENTIALS` - Azure service principal credentials
- `DB_ADMIN_PASSWORD` - PostgreSQL administrator password
- `DEV_ALERT_RECIPIENTS` - Development alert email recipients (JSON)
- `PROD_ALERT_RECIPIENTS` - Production alert email recipients (JSON)

### ‚úÖ Testing Done

- [x] Terraform syntax validation
- [x] Module structure verification
- [x] Environment configuration validation
- [x] Deployment script testing
- [x] Documentation review

### üìù Files Changed

- **22 files added** with 3,569 lines of Terraform infrastructure code
- Complete modular Terraform structure
- Environment-specific configurations
- Automation scripts and documentation
- GitHub Actions CI/CD workflow

### üéØ Resolves

Closes #98

### üìö Additional Notes

This implementation provides a production-ready Terraform baseline that supports:
- Fresh environment creation from scratch
- Environment-specific configurations (dev/prod)
- Comprehensive monitoring and alerting
- Security best practices and compliance
- Cost optimization strategies
- Automated deployment workflows

The infrastructure is designed to be modular, reusable, and maintainable, following Terraform best practices and Azure Well-Architected Framework principles.

issue.title: CORS Error on User Registration: Unable to Register New Users from Frontend
issue.body:
When a user tries to register using the frontend application, the registration request fails due to a CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) error. The browser console displays an error message indicating that the backend server does not allow requests from the frontend‚Äôs origin.

### Steps to Reproduce
1. Open the registration page on the frontend.
2. Fill in all required registration fields.
3. Click the "Register" button.
4. Observe the error message in the browser console.

### Expected Behavior
The user should be able to register successfully, and no CORS errors should appear in the console.

### Actual Behavior
The registration fails, and a CORS error is shown in the browser console.

## Proposed Solution
Update the backend server to allow requests from the frontend origin by setting the appropriate CORS headers. This will enable successful communication between the frontend and backend during user registration.

pull_request.title: Refactor: Split large CLI command files into logical modules
pull_request.body:
## Summary

This PR refactors the large CLI command files into focused, maintainable modules. The refactoring improves code organization while maintaining 100% backward compatibility.

## Files Refactored

### üìß **`email.rs`** (867 lines ‚Üí 6 modules)
- **`analytics.rs`** - Email tracking and analytics functionality
- **`core.rs`** - Core email operations (send, setup)
- **`providers.rs`** - Provider operations (test, configure, switch)
- **`queue.rs`** - Queue operations (status, process, clear)
- **`templates.rs`** - Template management (list, validate, render)
- **`testing.rs`** - Testing/capture functionality (capture, list, show, clear, export)

### üîÑ **`queue.rs`** (795 lines ‚Üí 3 modules)
- **`queue_work.rs`** - Work processing functionality for background job execution
- **`queue_status.rs`** - Status monitoring functionality for queue inspection
- **`queue_scheduler.rs`** - Scheduled commands and daemon functionality for cron-like jobs

### üîê **`auth.rs`** (761 lines ‚Üí 3 modules)
- **`auth_setup.rs`** - Auth system setup and configuration
- **`auth_scaffold.rs`** - Scaffolding (user models, controllers, migrations)
- **`auth_generators.rs`** - Key generation functionality

### üÜï **`new.rs`** (492 lines ‚Üí 2 modules)
- **`new_app.rs`** - Main application creation functionality
- **`new_templates.rs`** - Template generation and file creation

### ‚öôÔ∏è **`interactive_setup.rs`** (410 lines ‚Üí 2 modules)
- **`interactive_wizard.rs`** - Interactive project setup wizard functionality
- **`interactive_config.rs`** - Configuration collection and generation

## Key Benefits

- ‚úÖ **Improved maintainability**: Each module has a single, focused responsibility
- ‚úÖ **Better code organization**: Related functionality is grouped together logically
- ‚úÖ **Enhanced readability**: Smaller, more manageable files are easier to navigate
- ‚úÖ **Zero breaking changes**: All existing functionality preserved with the same public API
- ‚úÖ **Consistent patterns**: Modular structure follows the same pattern across all commands
- ‚úÖ **Future development**: New features can be added to the appropriate module

## Testing

All functionality has been thoroughly tested:

- ‚úÖ **Build verification**: `cargo build` completes successfully with no errors
- ‚úÖ **CLI functionality**: All commands work exactly as before
- ‚úÖ **Help system**: All help commands display correctly
- ‚úÖ **Module integration**: Proper re-export structure maintains original public interface

### Command Testing Results
```bash
$ elifrs --help        # ‚úÖ Main help works
$ elifrs email --help  # ‚úÖ Email commands work  
$ elifrs queue --help  # ‚úÖ Queue commands work
$ elifrs auth --help   # ‚úÖ Auth commands work
```

## Technical Details

### Module Structure
Each refactored command follows this pattern:
```
crates/cli/src/commands/[command]/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ mod.rs              # Module declarations and re-exports
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ [command]_[area].rs # Focused functionality modules
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ [command]_[area].rs # Additional modules as needed
```

### Backward Compatibility
- All original imports continue to work without modification
- External code using these modules requires no changes
- All CLI commands maintain their exact same behavior and help text

## Code Quality

- **Focused modules**: Each module has a clear, single responsibility
- **Clean separation**: Related functionality is properly grouped
- **Consistent imports**: All dependencies correctly maintained across modules
- **Documentation**: Each module includes appropriate documentation
- **Error handling**: All original error handling logic preserved
